We need to assess whether described visualizations are misleading based on error list. We only have description; cannot see actual visual. Evaluate potential issues.

Pie charts for sex distribution and age distribution. Are they appropriate? For categorical proportions, pie charts are okay but can be misleading if many categories or small differences. Sex distribution: two categories, okay. Age distribution: four categories, okay. However total cases reported 611 but sum of age categories: 20+31+183+163 = 397. That's far less than total cases. So either missing categories (maybe others) or numbers are wrong. That suggests misleading: either cherry-picking (only showing subset) or incorrect data. Also the percentages given: they said majority 57% 41-60. Let's compute 183/397=46%, not 57%. So numbers inconsistent. So the analysis likely misinterprets or the visualization may have omitted many cases. Could be cherry-picking or issues with data validity. Also map lacking key: ambiguous encoding. That's unclear encoding. Also interpretation that low deaths suggests good recovery rate may be a causal inference? They say "suggests a good recovery rate and/or effective healthcare management". That's inference maybe ok but could be overinterpreting small sample; but not necessarily causal.

Also they state "The relatively low number of deaths (7) compared to the number of positive cases suggests a good recovery rate and/or effective healthcare management at the time." That could be causal inference without evidence.

Also they claim "The infographic effectively presents a snapshot". Might be overstatement.

Thus misleading aspects: Cherry-picking (age distribution incomplete), Issues with data validity (numbers don't sum to total), Unclear encoding (map lacks key), Potential causal inference.

We need to decide if overall visualization is misleading. Yes, because of cherry-picking and data inconsistency.

Confidence maybe 80.

Intentional? Hard to know. Could be unintentional oversight. Given official infographic, maybe they omitted other age groups purposely? Might be intentional to highlight older groups. I would assign moderate confidence that it's intentional, maybe 60.

Now rhetoric types: Information Access Rhetoric: yes, they chose which data to show (age groups selected, omitted others). Confidence high 90. Supports misleading (yes). Provenance Rhetoric: No mention of sources, methods; but the infographic may not show them. So likely absent. Confidence 80. Supports misleading? Absence of provenance may allow misleading; but not directly supporting. Could say false. Mapping Rhetoric: yes, map uses color intensity to represent cases. That's mapping. Confidence 85. Does it support misleading? The map lacks key, causing ambiguous interpretation, so mapping may be misleading. So supports misleading (yes). Linguistic-Based Rhetoric: captions, hashtags, language framing "good recovery rate". Yes. Confidence 80. Supports misleading (yes). Procedural Rhetoric: No interactive elements described. So false. Confidence 80.
